   This document describes an enhancement of the secured version of the
   TACACS+ protocol [RFC9887] to facilitate the download of the 
   applicable Public Keys from a central TACACS+ server so that the
   TACACS+ Client can use it to complete SSH authentication.
   The intent is to shift the burden of administration of SSH Public
   Keys from the Network Devices to the central TACACS+ Server.
   Note that this model does NOT extend the SSH authentication flow
   out from the SSH Server (The TACACS+ Client), to the TACACS+ 
   Server.  The authentication remains completely in the SSH
   Server (The TACACS+ Client).  It is important to keep this in mind,
   as the phase of the AAA protocol that is used to download the public
   Keys is actually the TACACS+ Authentication phase.

   Specifically, this document adds a new authentication action value
   into TACACS+ Authnentication flow, the reply to which, allows the
   TACACS+ Server to send the relevant SSH Public Keys to the device.

2.  Technical Definitions

   The terms defined in Section 2 of [RFC9887] are fully applicable here
   and will not be repeated.  The following terms are also used in this document.

2.1.  SSHST+

   An SSHST+ (SSH Server/TACACS+ Client).  This is the device that is
   running the SSH Server and is configured as a TACACS+ Client.

3.  SSH Public Key Distribution

   The following mechanism describes the process. This enhancement of TACACS+
   Protocol is only applicable to the TLS TACACS+ protocol.

3.1.  Authentication START Packet

   A new enumerated value is added for use within the action field of the 
   Authentication START Packet:

   TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_SEND_PUBLIC_KEYS := 0x05

3.2.  Authentication REPLY Packet

   A New enumerated value is added for use within the status section of the 
   Authentication REPLY Packet:

   TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_STATUS_MORE := 0x22

3.2.  SSH Key download process

   As a result of SSH connection attempt, an SSHST+ requires the public
   key for a user.





