   If no key is available, then it MAY initiate a TACACS+
   Authentication flow to retrieve the key from the TACACS+ Server.

   SSHST+ sends an Authentication Start packet with the action field set
   to TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_SEND_PUBLIC_KEYS defined in Section 3.1:

   1.  user = username

   2.  action = TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_SEND_PUBLIC_KEYS

   3.  priv_lvl = 0 XXX This field might not be 0; right?

   4.  authen_type = TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_TYPE_ASCII

   5.  service = TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_SVC_LOGIN

   The user field of the Authentication Start packet contains the
   username for which the public keys are required.

   The TACACS+ Server processes the start packet, extracting the
   username, and determines if it can provide the public keys which are
   applicable for the username. The source of public keys is not defined by
   this document.

   If public keys are not available, the server responds with
   status=TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_STATUS_FAIL.

   If public keys are available, the server responds with
   status=TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_STATUS_PASS if there is only one applicable key or
   TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_STATUS_MORE if there are more than one key. The Public Keys are encoded
   into the data field as described in Section 3.3.

   1.  status = TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_STATUS_PASS

   2.  server_msg = EMPTY

   3.  data (section 3.3)

   XXX We had a proposal for this; "PASS" seems weird.

   SSHST+ receives the Authentication Reply packet and extracts the
   public key from the data field.

   SSHST+ uses the public key to authenticate the user.  If there is a failure,
   but the status is TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_STATUS_MORE, then the SSHST+ can
   Send Authentication CONTINUE Packet with the data field set to the last SSH Key that was 
   Returned. The cycle can continue until the authentication passes or the Server runs out of keys. 
   When the TACACS+ Server sends the last key (or first key if there is only one), 
   it MUST respond with TAC_PLUS_AUTHEN_STATUS_PASS.

   XXX Comment/guidance about caching keys should be added.  Can a client
   cache?  for how long?  Does a tacacs flag control this?

   Authorisation and Accounting proceed as they would if the SSH key had been 
   provisioned by the administrator directly onto the SSHST+.

3.3 Encoding of SSH Public Key in Authentication Reply Packet

   The Public Key is encoded in the data field of the Authentication Reply 
   Packet as follows:

   1. The encoding as Text String and must conform to Section 3.7 of [rfc8907]

   2. The content is limited to 32716 characters. Any larger, the key MUST be treated
      as unavailable as described in section 3.2

   3. The syntax of the encoding MUST conform to [rfc4716] (OK, do we want thsi 
      Or the more common implementation in the field, that ignored this RFC)?

    XXX This requires much more thought.  maybe both should be supported?

